    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate leaning heavily on our elite power-speed archetypes to offset a few challenging pitching matchups. **Yordan Alvarez** (81.47) is the clear offensive anchor, boasting an elite xwOBA of .393 against Andre Pallante; he is the highest-rated play on our board, benefiting significantly from his prime spot in the #2 hole. Meanwhile, our stolen base strategy is firing on all cylinders despite facing some high-velocity arms. **Hyeseong Kim** (70.52) and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (65.41) are must-starts today, as their matchups against Ryan Feltner and Freddy Peralta\u2014specifically the slow delivery patterns of those opposing starters\u2014grant them a massive boost in stolen base probability. **Colt Keith** (69.64) also emerges as a high-floor play, with his platoon advantage and batting order stability providing a reliable core for our production.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved **Jerar Encarnacion**, whose score of 45.63 fell just short of displacing our lower-end lineup pieces. While **Jerar Encarnacion** profiles well, the optimizer prioritized the stolen base upside of **Victor Scott II** (60.94) and the positional necessity of our catchers. We are proceeding with caution regarding **Trea Turner** (55.22) and **Kyle Schwarber** (53.83); both face the formidable Chris Sale, whose 2.88 xERA serves as a significant drag on their raw output. While their elite talent levels prevent us from benching them entirely, the SP Skill penalty against such an elite arm effectively caps their ceiling today. \n\nWe are monitoring all lineups closely, as \"Lineup Pending\" status on several key contributors\u2014including **Dillon Dingler**, **Gary Sanchez**, and **Kazuma Okamoto**\u2014introduces volatility into our projected scores. **Chase Meidroth** (55.94) remains a volatile but necessary start given the favorable park factors and the +15% SP skill adjustment provided by the matchup against Luis Severino. Should any of our assumed batting orders shift downward, we may see further degradation in these efficiency scores, but for now, we are comfortable with this configuration as we balance our need for power with our organizational mandate to maximize stolen base opportunities.",
